The acrostic arguments were written by a grammarian of the time of the Antonines, when the early comedy was a subject of grammatica] study and comment, or less probably at the period of the first Plautine revival, 150—50 B.C. The limitations of the artifi- cial form appear in the awkward- ness of the language: aliurn for alterum, 2 and 93 amittatur for amitteretur, 73 the omission of the subject of amittatur and of agnoscit, 9; and the obscurity of is, 8.
